54. print
      Prints the values of primitives and literals into the console, returns the printed string
      Syntax:
      "..."      <- denotes a string literal
      ${...}      <- denotes a variable within a string literal
      x = print(var)      var = 5            Output: "5"
      or
      x = print("text")                      Output: "text"
      or
      x = print("text with ${var}")          Output: "text with 5"

      Escape sequences:
      \n = newline       
      \t = tab        '      '   (4 spaces)
      \" = quote      '"'
      \${...} = actually ${...}  (Note that "${text moretext" is purely a string literal with no variable interpolation)

      Also note that you can make statements and do math within ${...} interpolations. i.e - ${2 + 2} would be converted to string literal "4"
      In fact, you can also enter newlines into ${...} and compute long and complex calculations within them.
      Example: print("text with ${x = 5,          prints string literal "text with 15".
                                  y = 10, 
                                  x + y}") 

